e><gtr:surname>Saha</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI01554X%2F1"><gtr:id>6EC42F8E-11BA-44DE-A569-FD691FA1EB70</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Postcolonial Cultural Economy: The Politics of British Asian Cultural Production</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I01554X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The aim of this fellowship is to disseminate research conducted on representations of race in the media.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Focusing on British Asian cultures, the aim of the research was to unravel why despite the greater participation of Asians in the media, negative representations of 'Asianness' still persist. While this has been a much-discussed issue there has been comparatively little work on how cultural industries work to reproduce racial and ethnic stereotypes. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In response, the research conducted an institutional ethnography of media production, focusing on the individuals and processes behind the representation of Asians in the media. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>What was discovered was a different kind of institutional racism, where it is the increasingly influence of commercial rationale that steers the work of creative workers in ways that eventually lead to the reproduction of stereotypical images of race. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>While recent initiatives have attempted to address this by increasing the number of individuals from BME groups working in the media, the research argues that this will have limited effects. Rather, it is only through changing the actual structures of the cultural industries and making more provision for independent work, that we will see better representations of minorities and a more inclusive version of Britishness as a whole.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>74161</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>547AF57C-EC14-4140-AE8C-30C314FD261B</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Routledge Companion to the Cultural Industries</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/894b54d8f6f213ece43de16a736506be"><gtr:id>894b54d8f6f213ece43de16a736506be</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Saha A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>978-0415706209</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>58c7d5ad3b2ab7.90155041</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2EF41B07-6450-4463-9107-9174DE0AE0BB</gtr:id><gtr:title>'Beards, scarves, halal meat, terrorists, forced marriage': television industries and the production of 'race'</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Media, Culture &